That’s actually a strong art-direction mechanic for a kids activity book because it creates visual mode switching instead of every page feeling identical.

You could structure it like this:

* Pallet Town → soft anime / classic watercolor style
* Pewter City → vintage Game Boy / Ken Sugimori-inspired ink style
* Cerulean → bright aquatic trading-card holo aesthetic
* Lavender Town → darker ghost-card style with hidden Gengar cameos
* Celadon → busy marketplace page with “booster pack” composition framing
* Safari Zone → field-guide / explorer sketchbook style
* Cinnabar Island → dramatic promo-card legendary scene
* Victory Road → epic splash-page with dozens of evolved Pokémon hidden

Then each page could secretly contain:

* 1 “common” hidden Pokémon
* 1 “rare”
* 1 “ultra rare”
* 1 “mythic cameo”
* and maybe a hidden trainer or item

The cool part is the transition between book and cards:

Book → Card Pipeline

Each hidden Pokémon could later become:

* a collectible “Found in Kanto” promo card
* a postcard
* a sticker
* a holo variant
* or an AR scan unlock

Example:
A tiny hidden Lapras in Cerulean City becomes:

* “Cerulean Harbor Lapras”
* full art water-card illustration later
* same pose/location from the puzzle page

That creates continuity kids LOVE:

“I FOUND THIS ONE IN THE BOOK!”

You could even do:

* “First Edition Hidden Sightings”
* map coordinates on cards
* checklist completion rewards
* faux Pokédex entries tied to scenes

Artistically, alternating styles every few pages also helps:

* attention reset
* novelty retention
* collectible feel
* replay value

And from a production standpoint, it lets different illustrators contribute distinct visual identities while still fitting the same world.